# Platform Integration: Cursor / Codex

When using Cursor or any Codex-based editor, the AI assistant is part of the Forge AI Web Builder system. 

The user will call upon you using the `@` mention syntax for a specific file, or by typing `@web-builder`.

## 🚀 How to trigger the builder:
When the user says `@web-builder` or asks to start the development pipeline, you MUST immediately read `agents/WEB_BUILDER_AGENT.md` and `BUILDER.md` to understand your role.

## 📜 Global Rules
- **Rule 1:** Always read `agents/WEB_BUILDER_AGENT.md` at the start of a session to understand the orchestration process.
- **Rule 2:** Use the slash commands defined in `platform/commands/MASTER_COMMANDS.md`.
- **Rule 3:** All code generation must adhere to `platform/skills/CORE_SKILLS.md`.
- **Rule 4:** Before marking a task as complete, you MUST run the verification steps defined in `PHASED_IMPLEMENTATION_PLAN.md`.

## 🛠 Active Agents (Reference these files)
- Orchestrator: `agents/WEB_BUILDER_AGENT.md`
- Frontend: `agents/FRONTEND_AGENT.md`
- Backend: `agents/BACKEND_AGENT.md`
- Infrastructure: `agents/CLOUD_ARCHITECT_AGENT.md`
- Security: `agents/AUTH_AGENT.md`
- Debugging: `agents/DEBUGGER_AGENT.md`

## 📡 Synchronization
Use `npx ts-node server/src/cli.ts` to execute tasks and sync progress.
